{
  "text": "Finally, it is known that the synthesis of macrophage derived proinflammatory cytokines can be triggered by a glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI)-anchor structure of T. cruzi [CITATION_1] , a glycolipid reminiscent of a lipopolysaccharide (LPS)-like structure of T. cruzi [CITATION_2] . This finding, together with the stimulant activity of LPS on TNF-a release [CITATION_3] , led us to explore the circulating levels of TNF-a and its soluble receptors when T. cruzi-infected C57BL/6 and BALB/c mice were challenged with LPS.",
